#Day 1 of Linux Skills 

1.man- command that displays a manual of that command
Example:
• man echo

2.cd- Command that changes directory
Example:
• cd <DIRECTORY PATH>

3.ls- Command that list files
Example:
• ls Display all the name files
• ls -a List all files including hidden directories
• ls -l Display files in a long list including file permissions
• ls -r Display files in a reverse order
• ls -R Display subdirectories recursively
• ls -t Display files by time 
• ls -h Display file size in human format

4.cat- Command that read and writes files
Example:
• cat <FILENAME>.txt
• cat -n Display the number of lines that a file haves.
• cat filename;filename2;filename3 Display all the files 
• cat filename > filename2 Redirects a existing file into a new file 
• cat filename >> filename2 appends in existing file by using >>
• cat -e filename It will display if the file haves spaces between paragraphs
• cat -T It will display if the file haves TAB spaces

5.mkdir- Command that creates a folder.
Example mkdir <FOLDERNAME>
• mkdir dirname1 dirname2 Creates 2 folder names separated
• mkdir -p dirname1/dirname2/dirname3 Creates multiple folders with a parent folder

6.Touch- Command that creates text files.
Example:
• touch file.txt Creates a text file called file.txt
• touch file1 file2 file3 Creates multiple files
• touch -a file.txt it will update the file if the file exist
• touch -t YYMMDDHHMM.SS file.txt Creates a file with a assign date and time.
• touch -r file1 file2 Creates a file with the timestamp of the first file
